    "summary": "Character alone is too ambiguous in running text",
    "content": "**Strongest objection to bare \"character\"**: Ambiguity in running text without a modifier.\n\n\"The character of a person\" in English defaults to meaning personality or moral character. \"A character in the story\" means a fictional person. \"Chinese characters\" means 汉字. The reader must disambiguate every occurrence. With \"inherent character\" or \"constitutive character,\" the modifier locks in the intended sense -- \"the quality that makes a thing what it is\" -- and the reader never has to guess.\n\nIf 性 is confirmed off the table, I would accept **\"constitutive character\"** as a strong alternative to \"inherent character.\" The adjective does the essential disambiguating work either way. Bare \"character\" does not."
  }
